habitat_description:
Phalacrocorax penicillatus nests on rocky headlands (Howell, 1917; Sowls et al., 1980; Speich and Wahl, 1989; Wallace and Wallace, 1998), rocky ledges on cliffs and slopes (Ray, 1904; Manuwal and Campbell, 1979; Sowls et al., 1980; Jones et al., 2008), and on rocky flats (Jones, 1909; Carter and Hobson, 1998; Wallace and Wallace, 1998; Jones et al., 2008). Nesting on man-made structures is rare, but has been documented (Couch and Lance, 2004).

Winter roosts are on rocks and islets (Campbell et al., 1990), sand flats and beaches (Howell, 1917; Wallace and Wallace, 1998), and headlands (Wallace and Wallace, 1998).

Brandt’s cormorant forages in open water (Speich and Wahl, 1989; Wallace and Wallace, 1989).

The species is rarely found farther than 10 km from land (Briggs et al., 1987).
